In Scandinavia oriental brassica is normally grown in the spring and fall, because they bolt in the summer heat. We only had one summer day in July. Temperature around 18-20Â°C â€” so why not try to grow a favourite out of season ? They still bolt, so there's no cut & regrow, only one happy harvest. Nature peeking through at 
At Impact Roasters, we believe that it is important to invest in job creation projects for the youth that resides in the areas where our coffee comes from. One of the projects that we have carried out through our nonprofit organization called Coffeeprint4Change is a concrete block production facility that employs local young men and women committed to being part of our aim to change and shape the local community. The training has already taken place, and now Coffeeprint4Change plans to develop other projects such as building schools, sanitation, facilities, libraries and other constructions that are needed to impact the whole community positively.

Valby Skole. I previously posted Valby Skole, daytime in October. This is how it looks nighttime. Itâ€™s holiday for the students, but about this time a day, some of them normally get to school, poor kids. The architect was Hans Peter Jacobsen (1877-1943). When it closed in the 1980s, the school moved in.

More Carlsberg - probably the oldest arse-grabbing in town... (pic. 3)  Carlsberg City District is a small area in Vesterbro in Copenhagen, bordering to the Frederiksberg and Valby districts. The area is named after Carlsberg's beer, which was brewed on the premises from 1847 - 2008. However the visitor centre Visit Carlsberg and Jacobsen House Brewery, which produces special brews, are still located here.  The Carlsberg grounds are currently being transformed into a new, but historic, neighbourhood called Carlsberg City District and is welcoming new tennants like educational instiutions, shops, cafÃ©s and its very own S-train station: Carlsberg Station.

This week's commute - through Carlsberg.  Carlsberg City District is a small area in Vesterbro in Copenhagen, bordering to the Frederiksberg and Valby districts. The area is named after Carlsberg's beer, which was brewed on the premises from 1847 - 2008. However the visitor centre Visit Carlsberg and Jacobsen House Brewery, which produces special brews, are still located here.  The Carlsberg grounds are currently being transformed into a new neighbourhood called Carlsberg City District and is welcoming new tennants like educational instiutions, shops, cafÃ©s and its very own S-train station: Carlsberg Station.

J. C. Jacobsen (1811-1887) Founder of world famous Carlsberg Breweries, named after his son, Carl and the hill (bjerg or berg) near the then small village Valby. Like the editors of Politivennen, Jacobsen was captain of the Copenhagen civil militsia, BorgervÃ¦bningen, and minded for the bourgeois society. His relations to his son Carl (1842-1914), founder of Ny Carlsberg, 1871 deteriorated over the years, They never reconciled. @carlsberg @carlsbergbyen

Valby Station, early morning. This is where most of my hikes start - and end. The station is the second (1911), the first existed 1847-1864. Tracks for international, national, local and metropolitan lines, the latter shown on the photo, from 1934. In 1950-1953 the station expanded. I dag den 10. november er det 170 Ã¥r siden â€“ hurra hurra  - at den fÃ¸rste bryg blev sat over pÃ¥ Carlsberg i Valby. Det var J.C. Hotel & Restaurant Fy & Bi, Valby. Halloween is an ancient celtic tradition (Samhain) to celebrate witches, ghosts and the dark powers. Christianity (catholicism) tried to it take over, and called it Allehelgensaften, All Saints Evening. Protestants disliked catholic traditions, so in 1770, it was abolished. But since 2000 the celtic tradition has been transformed and returned from the USA, and orange pumpkins with lights inside can be seen everywhere. Mwa ha hah!

Valby Skole 1917, architect Hans Peter Jacobsen (1877-1943). Any passenger passing Valby by train must admire these beautiful old industrial buildings, now housing Valby Skole. They were built for PorcelÃ¦nsfabrikken Norden (now Royal Copenhagen). The factory produced high resistant porcelain, able to resist 2 million Volt. When it closed in the 1980s, the school moved in.

Trekroner Bryggeri. The factory was established 1899, and was meant to house the brewery from 1899, designed by Caspar Leuning Borch. Only one third of the brewery is left. A war broke out between Carlsberg and De forenede Bryggerier, the latter swallowing up the brewery even before it moved in. The last beer left the factory in 1915, and was used by the tannery Ballin & Hertz. The building was modyfied for that purpose 1919-20 by architect Niels Hauberg. 30 years ago it was meant to be torn down, but luckily saved by unions and now used by the childrensâ€™ organization BÃ¸rns VilkÃ¥r.

Pilestykket, Husvildebarakker,  1947. 72 barracks, designed by architect Frederik Christian Lund (1896-1984). Functionalism. They were made in Sweden, still painted â€œSwedish Redâ€, and made for German refugees from refugee camp KlÃ¸vermarkslejren. When they returned to Germany, the barracks were used for homeless. It was meant as a temporary solution, but later facilities were added and they still exist for permanent use. The lampposts in the background is the stadion Valby IdrÃ¦tspark. â€œSpinderietâ€, Valby. The cotton factory (left) was build 1907 and closed by the end of the 1950s. It had its own nursery, SpindegÃ¥rden 1948-1965. Typical textile industry building with many and large windows to bring light inside. Then local crafters and industries moved in, until a shopping center was designed with old and new buildings 2007. Unlike many other shopping centers, is partly outdoor with a glass roof. Legendary union boss (SiD), Hardy Hansen (b. 1933) worked here for a short time until 1954.

Second session today was a skill focused two-piece workout. A) AMRAP 20 of 2 RMU and 6 dumbbell OHS (30kg/70lbs) B) 3 RFQ of 15 alt. dumbbell snatch (30kg/70lbs) with switch in the ground.  The A-piece would've been conditioning work if RMU's weren't such a skill/strength bottleneck and the OHS had been a bit lighter. I managed 12 rounds+2 RMU (26 RMU and 72 OHS) while only pushing my rest times in the last 5 minutes. Obviously still a glaring weakness, but I made some good technique improvements. I found a much tighter spot to hit in my kip that made the turnover much faster.  @stronghealthfitness
